  "prompt": "What language was spoken in the period of Lord Rama?",
  "response": "The period of Lord Rama, as described in the ancient Indian epic **Ramayana**, is traditionally dated to the **Treta Yuga**, which is believed to have occurred several millennia BCE. The language spoken during this time is considered to be an early form of **Sanskrit**, often referred to as **Vedic Sanskrit**. \n\nVedic Sanskrit is the language of the Vedic texts, such as the **Vedas**, **Brahmanas**, and **Aranyakas**, which were composed during this era or slightly later. The Ramayana itself was composed in **Classical Sanskrit** by the sage Valmiki, but the events it narrates are set in a time when Vedic Sanskrit was likely the spoken language of the elite and priestly classes.\n\nHowever, it's important to note that ancient India was linguistically diverse, and various regional dialects and Prakrits (early forms of vernacular languages) likely coexisted alongside Sanskrit, especially among the common people. The exact linguistic landscape of the time remains a subject of scholarly research and debate.",
